There’s no one size fits all when it comes to fueling 🍌

Finding what works best for you and your body takes a lot of trial and error & is best done during your training runs 🏃🏻‍♀️

Recently, I’ve learned that my body needs more than I thought. This 12 miler felt great- especially taking a gel before the run. Next time, I will take that first intra run gel a little quicker, maybe 30-40 minutes in instead and the next one 60-80 minutes in. I’ll constantly tweak until I get it perfect 🤩 

Remember, the key is to fuel before you feel like your body needs it. Otherwise, you’ve waited too long.

Guess what?! You can conquer the marathon with a low-volume approach and still achieve your goals! 🏁

You do not NEED to constantly run double digit miles every week leading up to a marathon. The runners you see doing this have likely been running for years and have bodies that are accustomed to it. But there’s no one size fits all. 

I ran my first marathon in 3:40 with my peak week mileage around 40. 

Sometimes, it’s not about how many miles you log, but the quality of those miles. Here’s how a lower mileage approach works:

1️⃣ Run Smart: Make sure each run has a purpose, whether it’s speed, endurance, or recovery.

2️⃣ Listen to Your Body: Low volume means less wear and tear. Pay attention to your body’s signals, rest when needed, and prevent burnout.

3️⃣ Cross-Training: Incorporate strength training, biking, or other activities to improve overall fitness without pounding the pavement constantly.

4️⃣ Recovery: Adequate rest and nutrition are key. Your body needs time to repair and adapt, even with fewer miles.

If you’re considering a low-volume marathon training approach, know that success is within reach. 🌟 Embrace the balance, train smart, and chase your marathon dreams with confidence. 

I am a big advocate of this approach- especially if you haven’t been running a long time or are injury prone. Check out the link in my bio for my training plans 🏃‍♂️ 🏃🏻‍♀️

Got a half marathon on the training schedule tomorrow so I felt really lucky to find @shewolfraces and have a race line up perfectly with my training 🏁

I typically do my long runs solo so it’ll be so nice to be alongside other runners and experience a race day vibe before my marathon 🏃🏻‍♀️

I always do these 4 things the days leading up to a race:

🏃🏻‍♀️ Shake out run: I get antsy the day before a race and an easy run helps me loosen up my muscles and mentally prepare me for the race. 

🥯 Eat more carbs: I find that slightly increasing my carb intake makes a huge difference in helping to sustain my performance throughout the race

💦 Drink water + electrolytes: Being on top of my hydration will reduce the risk of dehydration and cramps during the race- going with @drinklmnt today!

🧠 Establish a mantra or 2: The race will get tough at some point. Having a mantra ready will boost my mental resilience 

I’m so excited for tomorrow 🤩

If you’re training for a race, chances are you’re going to ask yourself several times throughout your training cycle, “Why am I putting myself through this?” 

Training is HARD. And you’re going to have plenty of days where you question it all and feel unmotivated. It’s why we can’t ever rely on motivation. 

It’s completely normal to have these thoughts and important to just continue to keep your eyes on the prize and push through. The unmotivated days give you a chance to prove you can maintain consistency, stay disciplined and build mental toughness.

It’s SO tempting to increase mileage too quickly or push yourself too hard and ignore the 80/20 rule…especially if you’re always comparing yourself to other runners. 

I can’t emphasize enough how important it is for newer runners to start gradually and listen to their bodies to avoid overexertion and ensure a safe, sustainable running journey. 

Doing too much too soon often leads to burn out and injury. One of the very best things a runner can do is focus on themselves- you’ll enjoy the journey so much more 🤠

Finding a fueling strategy can be SO intimidating. 

There’s several options and opinions out there and the way everyone’s body responds is completely different. 

Over the past several weeks, I have used @thefeedme to try different brands and types of intra run nutrition products for my long runs to be prepared for my upcoming marathon. Finding the perfect fuel came down to 2 things for me:

1. Do I like this?
2. How does it make me feel?

Enjoying what you’re consuming is important because after a certain mileage, consuming anything can become hard to stomach. And obviously, you want to know and feel like what you’re consuming you is giving you that much needed energy to avoid bonking. 

I tried countless products and found that @guenergylabs gels work best for me. I enjoy the chocolate flavors, the caffeine boost and feel like they provide me momentum to get though high mileage. 

Don’t forget to practice the timing of your nutrition- Personally, taking mine every 35 minutes when running 10 or more miles works best for me🍫

IT’S PEAK WEEK ⛰️ 

I truly cannot believe how fast this training cycle has gone by. My long run this week will be 20 miles and that’s the furthest I’ll go before 26.2! 🏃🏻‍♀️ 

If you saw my stories, you know that I skipped my long run this past weekend. I was supposed to go 14 miles, but I was playing a ton of tennis all weekend and getting poor sleep, so I decided I wasn’t going to further strain my body 💤 

Although I truly hate not following my schedule, I felt ok about skipping. I’ve been incredibly consistent, have continued to gradually increase mileage and have incorporated a mix of different types of runs. I feel confident in where I’m at and know that adjusting and moving on was the smartest decision for me 💪🏼

Today’s run felt glorious 🙌🏼 The leaves are beautiful in GA right now🍁 Have a great week!!

Marathon number 2 didn’t go quite as expected, but every race can be a learning opportunity. Here are my top takeaways:

1. You can do everything right in training and still not have race day go your way. And it’s ok to be bummed & proud at the same time 🫶🏻
 
2. Support is everything. This was a small marathon and I truly was ok with the lack of crowd support, but had Chris not found me several times at the end and encouraged me to keep going, I don’t think I would’ve made the under 4 hour mark 👫🏻

3. Try to stay calm. As soon as I  began to freak out about holding pace, it was hard to recover 💆🏻‍♀️

4. Hydration is not to be underestimated. I don’t think I was prepared for how much I’d be sweating 🥵 

Still chasing that 3:30 and I know I can get there 💪🏼

Gradually adding some speed work back in has felt great! If you’ve been around a while, you know I love progression runs. 

Here’s why:

1. It’s mentally easier to start slower- it takes the pressure off and makes starting a run more enjoyable.

2. They help prevent injury- starting slower is like an extension of your warm up and gives you time to evaluate your form and how your body is feeling. 

3. They help with my mental and physical toughness- in the past, I have struggled with finishing strong at the end of a race. Progression runs help me practice the discipline to manage my pace, keeping my body and mind strong. 

4. They’re exciting- sometimes you need a way to spice up a run. Aiming for negative splits is a way to challenge yourself and make sure those runs are never dull.

Tis the season for goal setting and forming habits ✨

You don’t need a new year to do this, but January always feels like a fresh start to me and I love the chance to write down what I want to accomplish in the coming year. 

Goals and habits go hand in hand. Habits help enable goals. Here’s 3 hacks I use to make habits stick:

1. Start small. Instead of trying to make significant changes all at once, start with tiny, manageable habits. As the habit becomes ingrained, you can gradually increase the difficulty or duration if you want to. 

2. Use habit stacking. Pair your new habit with an existing one, so that it’s easier to remember and integrate into your routine. 

3. Reward yourself. Find a way to provide positive reinforcement, making a habit more enjoyable. I am all about finding a way to treat yoself ( Tom Haverford style 😅). 

Consistency is crucial. Be patient with yourself and celebrate, small victories along the way 👊🏼
